result.execSummary:
The defendant Sheena R. Tuckwab was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Business Setting <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Sheena R. Tuckwab in court with attorney John E Voorhees.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 9:50 AM. State - resolved - plead g/nc to count #1 as alleged, #2 - DRl, joint recommendation of a withheld sentence and place on probation for 1 year with conditions of: $220.00 restitition to Mole Lake Conveneince Store including VW surcharge, costs, AODA and follow thru, absolute sobriety and no possession or entry, obtain/maintain employment/school, 100 hours of community service. Voorhees and Tuckwab agree. Court dismisses and reads in count #2 and explains what that means. Tuckwab pleads G to count #1. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights by entering her plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - was not going to ask for probation if restitution would be paid in full prior to today. Discussion on restitution. Court will not be ordering restitution. State then willing to change offer to no probation and just a fine of $300.00 plus costs on count #1. Voorhees and Tuckwab would agree with that. Voorhees makes final statement prior to sentencing. Tuckwab makes statement, remorseful. Court sentences the defendant to the following: count #1 - $300.00 fine plus costs - 60 DTP/CO, ordering $20.00 VW surcharge - 60 DTP/CO, no restitution ordered, submit DNA sample, right to appeal, adjourned.
Plea/sentencing hearing on November 30, 2016 at 04:00 pm.
Jury trial on December 2, 2016 at 08:30 am.
